English language|English, in various dialects, is the most widely spoken language of the United Kingdom,<ref>cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/uk/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780521794886|title=Home|website=Cambridge University Press</ref> however there are a number of regional languages also spoken. There are 14 indigenous languages used across the British Isles: 5 Celtic languages|Celtic, 3 Germanic languages|Germanic, 3 Romance languages|Romance, and 3 sign languages. There are also many immigrant languages spoken in the British Isles, mainly within inner city areas; these languages are mainly from South Asia and Eastern Europe.

The ''de facto'' official language of the United Kingdom is English,<ref name=keyfacts/><ref name="direct.gov.uk"/> which is spoken by approximately 59.8 million residents, or 98% of the population, over the age of three.<ref name=EnglishCensus>According to the United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census, 53,098,301 people in England and Wales, 5,044,683 people in Scotland, and 1,681,210 people in Northern Ireland can speak English "well" or "very well"; totalling 59,824,194. Therefore, out of the 60,815,385 residents of the UK over the age of three, 98% can speak English "well" or "very well".</ref><ref name=bbclang>cite web|title=United Kingdom|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/languages/european_languages/countries/uk.shtml|work=Languages Across Europe|publisher=BBC|accessdate=21 November 2013</ref><ref>Scotland's Census 2011 – Proficiency in English, All people aged 3 and over.</ref><ref>Northern Ireland Census 2011 – Main language and Proficiency in English, All usual residents aged 3 and over.</ref><ref>ONS census, [http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/QS205EW/view/2092957703?cols=measures QS205EW – Proficiency in English]. Retrieved 15 March 2015.</ref> An estimated 700,000 people speak Welsh language|Welsh in the UK,<ref name=WelshStatOverview>[https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20120330040554/http://www.byig-wlb.org.uk/English/publications/Publications/A%20statistical%20overview%20of%20the%20Welsh%20languagef2.pdf Bwrdd yr Iaith Gymraeg, A statistical overview of the Welsh language], by Hywel M Jones, page 115, 13.5.1.6, England. Published February 2012. Retrieved 28 March 2016.</ref> an official language in Wales<ref>cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/mwa/2011/1/section/1/enacted |publisher=The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives |work=legislation.gov.uk |title=Welsh Language (Wales) Measure 2011 |accessdate=30 May 2016</ref> and the only ''de jure'' official language in any part of the UK.<ref>cite web|title=Welsh Language Measure receives Royal Assent |url=http://wales.gov.uk/newsroom/welshlanguage/2011/110211welshlang/?lang=en |work=Welsh Government |accessdate=21 November 2013 |date=11 February 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922140142/http://wales.gov.uk/newsroom/welshlanguage/2011/110211welshlang/?lang=en |archivedate=22 September 2013 |df=dmy</ref> Approximately 1.5 million people in the UK speak Scots language|Scots—although Scots language#Status|there is debate as to whether this is a distinct language, or a variety of English.<ref name=SCOTSCENSUS/><ref name="English Language 1992. p.894">A.J. Aitken in ''The Oxford Companion to the English Language'', Oxford University Press 1992. p.894</ref>

There is some discussion of the languages of the United Kingdom's three Crown dependencies (Jersey, Guernsey and the Isle of Man),<ref>cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/about/moj/our-responsibilities/Background_Briefing_on_the_Crown_Dependencies2.pdf|title=Background briefing on the Crown Dependencies: Jersey, Guernsey and the Isle of Man|publisher=Ministry of Justice|accessdate=9 March 2015|format=PDF</ref> though they are not part of the United Kingdom.

